title: Grateful Dead Live at Winterland Arena on 1977-12-27
lineage: Dat (Sony R500) > Tascam DA-3000 > Samplitude Pro X3 > FLAC
description:
Set 1

Bertha-> Good Lovin', Brown Eyed Women, Cassidy, Peggy-O, Looks Like Rain, Dire Wolf, Passenger, Candyman, El Paso, Friend Of The Devil, The Music Never Stopped

Set 2

Cold Rain & Snow, Lazy Lightning-> Supplication, Scarlet Begonias-> Fire On The Mountain-> Estimated Prophet-> He's Gone-> Truckin'-> Wharf Rat-> Around & Around, E: Samson & Delilah

reviews.review_text: Sound quality I try to stay away from reviewing performances as it is such a subjective topic, but sound quality....good god this one is crisp! A million thanks to the people that make this stuff available.

Note Sam
Nov & Dec '77 was one of the hottest periods; a string of 8 incredible shows. 11/4 & 12/29 are astonishing and the NYE run is probably the best one overall. It's particularly known for 12/30, one of the best shows of all time. But the shoulder shows are are also worth hearing. This show is better than NYE itself and, though not as good as the next two, is as good as 11/2 Toronto & 11/5 Rochester. And, did you note the Samson as encore? The original circulating SBDs have a censored Wharf Rat and are missing the encore. First Set. The verses are flubbed for Bertha but the solo is insane. Good Lovin' is beautiful, just not tight. That changes for the exciting Brown Eyed Women. Listen to Bobby's rhythm and Keith, both beyond the call of duty. The Cassidy is hotter than soup, and Jer uses that advantage to make emphatic statements. Most of the rest is average '77, though with the shoes creeping into the dryer by Passenger. After Candyman, Bobby apparently makes a comment to the drummers, who in return threaten to take Bobby's watch. "They're criticizing your watch Bob!," Jer teases. Friend of the Devil is the best of the rest, though Music Never Stopped leaves 'em happy for the break. Second Set. Cold Rain & Snow is tight enough, but very straightforward. Seems like a 1st set opener. The last minute of Supplication is where things get hot again. Take your protein pills and put your helmet on for this Scarlet Begonias. The verses are great and I dig the lolloping solo, and love the little bits alongside the jam into Fire. The jam from Estimated>He's Gone is also nice, but Truckin' takes a powder. Wharf Rat is pretty rote until the jams, which turn over pebbles and find rocks. Clunky set finisher Around & Around is ameliorated by a one-of-a-kind encore Samson that brings the Xfac back one more time. 1st Set:  B- 2nd Set: C+ Overall = 3¼ stars Highlights: Brown Eyed Women - rhythm guitar great, Keith great Cassidy - Jer's emphatic statements Scarlet Begonias - lollops and extras [you'll probably want to check off Samson-as-an-encore, too] SOURCES: A Miller source finally appeared, without the censored Wharf Rat and the digital glitches in Lazy Lightning, and with a patched Around and with the encore! The sound quality is superb (though the channels are reversed and it needs boosted highs for the second set). If you compare the glitch in Lazy Lightning in the Ashley_Bertha source to the redbeard_3989, you'll hear the amount of reverb and EQ often coloring the Bertha-processed sources

Crunchy. Where that time machine? Quality 12 30 material. ever heard a bad 12 30 show? 
Not I. Maybe some other band.

Year end Winterland Always really fine shows at year end. This is a perfect example of nice set list,top playing by Weir, of course Jerry,and the rest. There are standouts, but I wont start a long,long review,we all have our preferences.
Try Nov. and Dec.of 71’ Pig, and the band are incredibly tight, and John Cutler at the time was producing shows with clear crisp sound. Love those shows, but here is a show 6 years later with the same drive and force as almost always! 
Keep the mother rollin………
